







#lg 28.1	proverb

@(A.28.1.1 = 1)  @note{cf. @xref[t.6.1.03,t.6.1.03.84]{6.1.03.84}} The battle-club does not find out his name, it just finds his flesh.

#lg 28.2	proverb

@(A.28.2.2 = 2)  The city may change its name, but let my name stand!

#lg 28.3	proverb

@(A.28.3.3 = 3)  The mongoose does not know fear of god.

#lg 28.4	proverb

@(A.28.4.4 = 4-5)  @note{cf. @xref[t.6.1.01,t.6.1.01.145]{6.1.01.145}, @xref[t.6.1.19,t.6.1.19.c3]{6.1.19.c3}, @xref[t.6.1.22,]{6.1.22: ll. 87-88}} Accept your lot and make your mother happy! Run fast and make your god happy!

#lg 28.5	proverb

@(A.28.5.6 = 6)  An eagle (?) enters a man's mouth.

#lg 28.6	proverb

@(A.28.6.7 = 7)  When a fly enters, your mouth will buzz @note{lit. @q{“fly”}}.

#lg 28.7	proverb

@(A.28.7.8 = 8-9)  @note{cf. @xref[t.6.1.15,t.6.1.15.c2]{6.1.15.c2}, @xref[t.6.1.26,t.6.1.26.b3]{6.1.26.b3}} Let the ox be struck with a stick and let the sheep be given the whip. Where there is no toughness, no one can go about their business, not even a plenipotentiary.

