#lg 28.24	proverb

@(B.28.24.29 = 29-30)  @note{cf. @xref[t.6.1.02,t.6.1.02.155]{6.1.02.155}, @xref[t.6.2.3,]{6.2.3: UET 6/2 209 ll. 1-3}, @xref[t.1.8.1.5,]{1.8.1.5: ll. 193-199}} The palace is a forest. The king, the lion, subdues men with a huge net like @wDN{Nungal}.

#lg 28.25	proverb

@(B.28.25.31 = 31)  @note{cf. @xref[t.6.1.03,t.6.1.03.41]{6.1.03.41}, @xref[t.6.1.19,t.6.1.19.d9]{6.1.19.d9}} When the mistress left the house and the slave girl came in from the street, away from her mistress the slave girl set up her own banquet.

#lg 28.26	proverb

@(B.28.26.32 = 32-33)  @note{cf. @xref[t.6.1.03,t.6.1.03.106]{6.1.03.106}} Where there is no grain, this is a sign of vengeance turned toward a city. Where there are no reeds, it is the worst of all poverty.

#lg 28.27	proverb

@(B.28.27.34 = 34-35)  @note{cf. @xref[t.6.1.03,t.6.1.03.148]{6.1.03.148}, @xref[t.6.1.22,]{6.1.22: ll. 191-193}} @q{“I bow over your thighs”} is what the leather-workers say. @q{“I swear by @wDN{Enki} that it will take no time at all”} is what the fullers say.

#lg 28.28	proverb

@(B.28.28.36 = 36-38)  @note{cf. @xref[t.6.1.03,t.6.1.03.112]{6.1.03.112}, @xref[t.6.1.22,]{6.1.22: ll. 19-20}, @xref[t.6.2.3,]{6.2.3: UET 6/2 311 ll. 4-5}} When the fish is too hot, let him cool it down for you and pick out the bones for you. …… go ……, I …… happy …….



